# EWW | ITandTEL Cloud Documentation - Cursor Project Rules

## Project Overview
This is a Hugo-based documentation website for EWW | ITandTEL Cloud platform (docs.ventuscloud.eu) using the hugo-theme-learn theme with custom branding.

## File Structure & Organization

### Content Structure
- `/content/` - Main documentation content in Markdown
- `/content/_index.md` - Homepage content
- `/content/getting-started/` - Chapter 1: User onboarding guides
- `/content/identity-management/` - Chapter 2: User and group management
- `/content/products/` - Chapter 3: Core cloud services documentation
- `/content/iac/` - Chapter 4: Infrastructure as Code guides
- `/content/tutorials-advanced/` - Chapter 5: Advanced scenarios

### Asset Organization
- `/content/assets/images/` - All documentation images organized by service:
  - `/account/` - Account management screenshots
  - `/vms/` - Virtual machine interfaces
  - `/databases/` - Database service images
  - `/networks/` - Networking screenshots
  - `/lb/` - Load balancer images
  - `/clusters/` - Kubernetes screenshots
  - `/backups/` - Backup service images
  - And 15+ other service-specific directories

### Configuration & Styling
- `/config.toml` - Hugo site configuration
- `/static/css/theme-mine.css` - Custom brand styling
- `/layouts/partials/` - Custom Hugo templates
- `/themes/hugo-theme-learn/` - Base theme (do not modify directly)

## Content Writing Guidelines

### Front Matter Format
Use TOML front matter for all content files:
```toml
+++
title = "Page Title"
date = 2019-09-25T01:53:09+03:30
weight = 10
chapter = true  # For index pages
pre = "<b>1. </b>"  # Chapter numbering
+++
```

### Content Structure Rules
1. **Chapter Index Pages** (`_index.md`):
   - Must have `chapter = true` in front matter
   - Include weight for proper ordering
   - End with `{{% children style="h4" depth="2" %}}`
   - Use chapter numbering in `pre` field

2. **Regular Pages**:
   - No `chapter = true` flag
   - Descriptive titles targeting technical users
   - Include step-by-step instructions
   - Reference screenshots with relative paths

### Writing Style
- **Audience**: DevOps engineers, system administrators, developers
- **Tone**: Professional, technical, instructional
- **Format**: Step-by-step guides with numbered lists
- **Screenshots**: Include relevant images for every major step
- **Code Examples**: Use proper syntax highlighting

### Formatting Guidelines
- **List Formatting**: In bulleted or numbered lists, the last item may include additional spacing for visual separation or emphasis when appropriate
- **Consistent Indentation**: Maintain consistent indentation levels throughout nested lists
- **Parallel Structure**: Keep list items in parallel grammatical structure

## Image Management Rules

### Image Naming Convention
- Use descriptive, numbered filenames: `1.png`, `2.png`, etc.
- For variations: `21-1.png`, `21.png`
- Place in service-specific directories under `/content/assets/images/`

### Image References
- Use relative paths: `![Description](mdc:../../assets/images/service-name/filename.png)` or `![Description](mdc:../../../assets/images/service-name/filename.png)` depending on directory depth
- Always include alt text for accessibility
- Keep images under 500KB when possible
- Use PNG format for screenshots
- Include Hugo parameters for styling: `?width=30pc&classes=border,shadow`

## Styling & Branding
### Color Scheme (defined in theme-mine.css)
- Primary brand color: `#0092cf`
- Hover color: `#0078c0`
- Menu background: `#252c31`
- Active sections: `#20272b`

### CSS Customization Rules
- Only modify `/static/css/theme-mine.css`
- Use CSS custom properties (variables) defined in `:root`
- Maintain consistent branding across all pages
- Center-align main headings and navigation elements

## Hugo-Specific Guidelines

### Shortcodes Usage
- Use `{{% children %}}` for automatic page listings
- Use `{{% notice note %}}` for important callouts
- Reference theme documentation for additional shortcodes

### Menu Configuration
- Weight determines menu order (lower = higher in menu)
- Use chapter structure for main sections
- Maintain consistent numbering scheme

### Search Functionality
- Ensure `outputs = ["HTML", "RSS", "JSON"]` in config.toml
- All content is automatically indexed
- Use descriptive titles and headings for better search results

## Development Workflow

### Local Development
- Run `hugo server -D` for development with drafts
- Use `hugo server --navigateToChanged` for automatic navigation
- Test all links and images before committing

### Content Updates
1. Create/edit Markdown files in appropriate `/content/` subdirectory
2. Add/update images in corresponding `/content/assets/images/` folder
3. Update front matter with correct weight and metadata
4. Test locally before deploying

### File Naming Conventions
- Use lowercase with hyphens: `virtual-machines.md`
- Match directory names to service categories
- Keep URLs SEO-friendly and descriptive

## Quality Standards

### Content Requirements
- Every guide must include screenshots for major steps
- Code examples must be tested and functional
- Links must be verified and working
- Technical accuracy is paramount

### Accessibility
- Include alt text for all images
- Use proper heading hierarchy (H1, H2, H3, etc.)
- Ensure color contrast meets standards
- Test with screen readers when possible

### SEO Optimization
- Use descriptive, keyword-rich titles
- Include meta descriptions where appropriate
- Optimize images with descriptive filenames
- Maintain consistent URL structure

## Deployment Notes
- Site builds automatically on changes to main branch
- Deployed to docs.ventuscloud.eu
- Hugo version compatibility maintained in CI/CD pipeline
- Static assets served from CDN for performance

## Common Tasks
- Adding new service documentation: Create subdirectory in `/content/products/`
- Updating screenshots: Replace files in appropriate `/content/assets/images/` subdirectory
- Modifying navigation: Update `weight` values in front matter
- Styling changes: Modify `/static/css/theme-mine.css` only

Remember: This documentation serves enterprise cloud platform users. Maintain professional quality, technical accuracy, and consistent branding throughout all content.
